# Git File Operations Rule

When working inside a git repository, use git commands instead of filesystem-only operations for moves, renames, and deletes.

## Required Commands

| Operation | Use | Never Use |
|-----------|-----|-----------|
| Move/Rename | `git mv <source> <target>` | `mv`, filesystem rename, or Delete+Write |
| Delete | `git rm <path>` | `rm`, `del`, or Delete tool alone |

## Why

`git mv` preserves file history across renames. Filesystem-only operations break `git log --follow` tracking — git sees a delete + unrelated new file instead of a rename.

## Scope

- Applies to all files tracked by git (or that will be committed)
- Does NOT apply to files in `.gitignore`, temp files, or build artifacts
- When creating new files, use normal tools — `git add` happens at commit time
